  "description": "<h2 id=\"introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<p>An accessible low flow canyon with nice views of the Needles climbing\narea towering overhead and of the Kern River at the end. Quality\ndegraded by low angle slabs that don't quite justify rappels (easily\nbypassed) and bushwhacking sections including minor poison oak and wild\nrose to avoid. The last rappel is the best, with a pleasant patio area\nat its base. Worth doing if you run out of things to check out in the\narea or everything else is too high flow. A wetsuit is not needed in\nmost conditions. Ample natural anchors.</p>\n<h2 id=\"approach\">Approach</h2>\n<p>Park at one of the two pullouts either side of Needlerock Creek and\nproceed down the creek.</p>\n<h2 id=\"descent\">Descent</h2>\n<p>Work your way down and around the slabby upper section. Alternatively\nthis could be a good area to practice rappelling with beginners or\nkids.</p>\n<p>Keep an eye out for poison oak and wild rose to avoid. There are also\na lot of sections with pine needles coating polished granite\n(slippery).</p>\n<p>Rappel 1: 40' from a tree on true left (fiddlesticked, no anchor).\nDown a granite slab rolling into an overhang with a vegetative finish.\nIt's possible this rappel may be bypassed with equal effort. From the\ntop anchor, 140' of rope is needed to Rappel the entire slab. There are\nseveral ledges with trees that can be used to reanchor.</p>\n<p>Continue down.</p>\n<p>There are several more slabs and ledges that are required to Rappel.\nNot everything has permanent anchors but there are plenty of trees to\nuse for retrievable anchors.</p>\n<p>Rappel 2: 80' minimum (slabby finish allows for a longer rappel if\ndesired) from small tree on true right (fiddlesticked, no anchor).</p>\n<p>Rappel 3: 40' from small tree on true right (fiddlesticked, no\nanchor). The watercourse goes down an interesting chute into a\nwaist-deep pool (ankle depth with finesse).</p>\n<p>Rappel 3 (alternate): About 50' from tree on true left. Probably a\nless awkward rappel. Dry. Awkward drop with alot of bushes in the\nwatercourse. It was unsafe to down climbed so there is webbing on a\nsmall tree left of the water course for a 50' Rappel.</p>\n<p>More thwacking.</p>\n<p>Rappel 4: 100' from very small rock arch and rock chock. Positions\nyou nicely on the edge of the left branch of the steep waterfall. Other\nanchor options exist. Nice patio area at the base of the falls with\nshallow pools and spray for those hot days.</p>\n<p>Downclimb the slabby V-crack about 40' to the river.</p>\n<h2 id=\"exit\">Exit</h2>\n<p>Once at the Kern River follow the riverbank upstream, climbing where\npossible (a little steep and loose). Continue steeply upward through\nmoderate scrub until you encounter the trail. Follow the trail back to\nyour car.</p>\n<h2 id=\"red_tape\">Red tape</h2>\n<h2 id=\"beta_sites\">Beta sites</h2>\n<h2 id=\"trip_reports_and_media\">Trip reports and media</h2>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>First documented canyoning descent by Nic Barth, Alden Anderson,\nScott Merrill, Pete Bohler, Sara Gallagher, and Celia Hoffman -- May\n24th, 2015 (low flow conditions: Kern River at 250 cfs)</p>\n",
